Certainly! Below is a simple example of a login system in Java using a console-based interface. This example will prompt the user to enter a username and password, and it will verify the credentials against predefined values.

### Example: Simple Console Login in Java

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class LoginSystem {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Predefined username and password
        String correctUsername = "admin";
        String correctPassword = "password123";

        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.println("Welcome to the Login System");

        // Prompt for username
        System.out.print("Enter username: ");
        String username = scanner.nextLine();

        // Prompt for password
        System.out.print("Enter password: ");
        String password = scanner.nextLine();

        // Validate credentials
        if (username.equals(correctUsername) && password.equals(correctPassword)) {
            System.out.println("Login successful! Welcome, " + username + ".");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid username or password. Login failed.");
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

### How to run:
1. Save the code in a file called `LoginSystem.java`.
2. Compile it using `javac LoginSystem.java`.
3. Run it using `java LoginSystem`.
4. When prompted, enter the username (`admin`) and password (`password123`) to successfully login.

